Indonesia Stocks: AKR Corporindo, Bank CIMB Niaga, Energi Mega

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-04-26T09:18:11Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-26/indonesia-stocks-adaro-energy-akr-corporindo-bank-cimb-niaga.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  declined 13.67 points, or 0.4
percent, to 3,774.87, falling for a second day.  Coal producers: PT Adaro Energy (ADRO IJ), the nation’s
second-largest coal mining company, slid 1.1 percent to 2,225
rupiah. PT Borneo Lumbung Energi & Metal (BORN IJ) dropped 1.7
percent to 1,690 rupiah.  Crude oil for June delivery fell as much as 1 percent to
$111.12 a barrel in after-hours trading in  New York . A lower oil
price reduces the appeal of alternative fuels such as coal.  PT AKR Corporindo (AKRA IJ), an Indonesian fuel and
chemical distributor, gained 4.4 percent to 1,670 rupiah, the
steepest increase since Feb. 23. The company said first-quarter
net income surged to 1.8 trillion rupiah ($208 million) from 70
billion rupiah a year earlier, boosted by the sale of a unit.  PT Bank CIMB Niaga (BNGA IJ), a unit of  Malaysia ’s CIMB
Group Holdings Bhd., climbed 1.1 percent to 1,820 rupiah, the
biggest gainer among  Indonesia ’s five largest banks by assets.
CIMB Niaga’s first-quarter net income advanced 39 percent from a
year earlier to 728 billion rupiah, the lender said in a
statement published in  Bisnis Indonesia .  PT Energi Mega Persada (ENRG IJ), the nation’s second-
largest listed oil company, jumped 8.5 percent to 153 rupiah,
the most since Dec. 1. Energi Mega said it posted first-quarter
net income of 14.3 billion rupiah compared with a net loss of
21.7 billion rupiah a year earlier.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net  